# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crossbeam-rust
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] In computing, a **channel** is a model for interprocess communication and synchronization via message passing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] A message may be sent over a channel, and another process or thread is able to receive messages sent over a channel it has a reference to, as a stream.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] Different implementations of channels may be buffered or not, and either synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The multithreading library, libthread, which was first created for the operating system Plan 9, offers inter-thread communication based on fixed-size channels.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The OCaml event module offers typed channels for synchronization.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] When the module's send and receive functions are called, they create corresponding send and receive events which can be synchronized.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The Love2D library which uses the Lua programming language implements channels with push and pop operations similar to stacks.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The pop operation will block so as long as there is data resident on the stack.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The XMOS programming language XC provides a primitive type "Chan" and two operators "<:" and ":>" for sending and receiving data from a channel.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] In this example, two hardware threads are started on the XMOS, running the two lines in the "par" block.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The first line transmits the number 42 through the channel while the second waits until it is received and sets the value of x.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] The XC language also allows asynchronous receiving on channels through a select statement.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] This snippet of Go code performs similarly to the XC code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] First the channel c is created, then a goroutine is spawned which sends 42 through the channel.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] When the number is put in the channel x is set to 42.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] Go allows channels to buffer contents, as well as non blocking receiving through the use of a select block.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] Rust provides asynchronous channels for communication between threads.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] Channels allow a unidirectional flow of information between two endpoints: the `Sender` and the `Receiver`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] In addition to their fundamental use for interprocess communication, channels can be used as a primitive to implement various other concurrent programming constructs which can be realized as streams.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] For example, channels can be used to construct futures and promises, where a future is a one-element channel, and a promise is a process that sends to the channel, fulfilling the future.
[src:crossbeam-rust/channel-programming] Similarly, iterators can be constructed directly from channels.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] In computer science, a **concurrent data structure** (also called **shared data structure**) is a data structure designed for access and modification by multiple computing threads (or processes or nodes) on a computer, for example concurrent queues, concurrent stacks etc.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The concurrent data structure is typically considered to reside in an abstract storage environment known as shared memory, which may be physically implemented as either a tightly coupled or a distributed collection of storage modules.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Concurrent data structures, intended for use in parallel or distributed computing environments, differ from "sequential" data structures, intended for use on a uni-processor machine, in several ways.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Most notably, in a sequential environment one specifies the data structure's properties and checks that they are implemented correctly, by providing **safety properties**.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] In a concurrent environment, the specification must also describe **liveness properties** which an implementation must provide.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Safety properties usually state that something bad never happens, while liveness properties state that something good keeps happening.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] These properties can be expressed, for example, using linear temporal logic.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The type of liveness requirements tend to define the data structure.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The method calls can be blocking or non-blocking.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Data structures are not restricted to one type or the other, and can allow combinations where some method calls are blocking and others are non-blocking (examples can be found in the Java concurrency software library).
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The safety properties of concurrent data structures must capture their behavior given the many possible interleavings of methods called by different threads.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] It is quite intuitive to specify how abstract data structures behave in a sequential setting in which there are no interleavings.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] To guarantee the safety and liveness properties, concurrent data structures must typically (though not always) allow threads to reach consensus as to the results of their simultaneous data access and modification requests.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] To support such agreement, concurrent data structures are implemented using special primitive synchronization operations (see synchronization primitives) available on modern multiprocessor machines that allow multiple threads to reach consensus.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] This consensus can be achieved in a blocking manner by using locks, or without locks, in which case it is non-blocking.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] There is a wide body of theory on the design of concurrent data structures (see bibliographical references).
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Concurrent data structures are significantly more difficult to design and to verify as being correct than their sequential counterparts.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The primary source of this additional difficulty is concurrency, exacerbated by the fact that threads must be thought of as being completely asynchronous: they are subject to operating system preemption, page faults, interrupts, and so on.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] On today's machines, the layout of processors and memory, the layout of data in memory, the communication load on the various elements of the multiprocessor architecture all influence performance.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Furthermore, there is a tension between correctness and performance: algorithmic enhancements that seek to improve performance often make it more difficult to design and verify a correct data structure implementation.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] A key measure for performance is scalability, captured by the speedup of the implementation.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Speedup is a measure of how effectively the application is using the machine it is running on.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] On a machine with P processors, the speedup is the ratio of the structures execution time on a single processor to its execution time on P processors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Ideally, we want linear speedup: we would like to achieve a speedup of P when using P processors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Data structures whose speedup grows with P are called **scalable**.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] The extent to which one can scale the performance of a concurrent data structure is captured by a formula known as Amdahl's law and more refined versions of it such as Gustafson's law.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] A key issue with the performance of concurrent data structures is the level of memory contention: the overhead in traffic to and from memory as a result of multiple threads concurrently attempting to access the same locations in memory.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] This issue is most acute with blocking implementations in which locks control access to memory.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] In order to acquire a lock, a thread must repeatedly attempt to modify that location.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] .NET have ConcurrentDictionary, ConcurrentQueue and ConcurrentStack in the System.Collections.Concurrent namespace.
[src:crossbeam-rust/concurrent-data-structure] Rust instead wraps data structures in Arc and Mutex.
[src:crossbeam-rust/latest-crossbeam] Multi-producer multi-consumer channels for message passing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/latest-crossbeam] Threads that can borrow variables from the stack.
[src:crossbeam-rust/latest-crossbeam] Selects from a set of channel operations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/latest-crossbeam] Creates a new scope for spawning threads.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In computer science, an algorithm is called **non-blocking** if failure or suspension of any thread cannot cause failure or suspension of another thread; for some operations, these algorithms provide a useful alternative to traditional blocking implementations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] A non-blocking algorithm is **lock-free** if there is guaranteed system-wide progress, and **wait-free** if there is also guaranteed per-thread progress.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] "Non-blocking" was used as a synonym for "lock-free" in the literature until the introduction of obstruction-freedom in 2003.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] The word "non-blocking" was traditionally used to describe telecommunications networks that could route a connection through a set of relays "without having to re-arrange existing calls" (see Clos network).
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Also, if the telephone exchange "is not defective, it can always make the connection" (see nonblocking minimal spanning switch).
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] The traditional approach to multi-threaded programming is to use locks to synchronize access to shared resources.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes, semaphores, and critical sections are all mechanisms by which a programmer can ensure that certain sections of code do not execute concurrently, if doing so could corrupt shared memory structures.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] If one thread attempts to acquire a lock that is already held by another thread, the thread will block until the lock is free.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Blocking a thread can be undesirable for many reasons.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] An obvious reason is that while the thread is blocked, it cannot accomplish anything: if the blocked thread had been performing a high-priority or real-time task, it would be highly undesirable to halt its progress.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] For example, certain interactions between locks can lead to error conditions such as deadlock, livelock, and priority inversion.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Using locks also involves a trade-off between coarse-grained locking, which can significantly reduce opportunities for parallelism, and fine-grained locking, which requires more careful design, increases locking overhead and is more prone to bugs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Unlike blocking algorithms, non-blocking algorithms do not suffer from these downsides, and in addition are safe for use in interrupt handlers: even though the preempted thread cannot be resumed, progress is still possible without it.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In contrast, global data structures protected by mutual exclusion cannot safely be accessed in an interrupt handler, as the preempted thread may be the one holding the lock.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] While this can be rectified by masking interrupt requests during the critical section, this requires the code in the critical section to have bounded (and preferably short) running time, or excessive interrupt latency may be observed.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] A lock-free data structure can be used to improve performance.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] A lock-free data structure increases the amount of time spent in parallel execution rather than serial execution, improving performance on a multi-core processor, because access to the shared data structure does not need to be serialized to stay coherent.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] With few exceptions, non-blocking algorithms use atomic read-modify-write primitives that the hardware must provide, the most notable of which is compare and swap (CAS).
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Critical sections are almost always implemented using standard interfaces over these primitives (in the general case, critical sections will be blocking, even when implemented with these primitives).
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In the 1990s all non-blocking algorithms had to be written "natively" with the underlying primitives to achieve acceptable performance.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] However, the emerging field of software transactional memory promises standard abstractions for writing efficient non-blocking code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Much research has also been done in providing basic data structures such as stacks, queues, sets, and hash tables.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] These allow programs to easily exchange data between threads asynchronously.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Additionally, some non-blocking data structures are weak enough to be implemented without special atomic primitives.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Several libraries internally use lock-free techniques, but it is difficult to write lock-free code that is correct.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Non-blocking algorithms generally involve a series of read, read-modify-write, and write instructions in a carefully designed order.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Optimizing compilers can aggressively re-arrange operations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Even when they don't, many modern CPUs often re-arrange such operations (they have a "weak consistency model"), unless a memory barrier is used to tell the CPU not to reorder.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] C++11 programmers can use `std::atomic` in `<atomic>`, and C11 programmers can use `<stdatomic.h>`, both of which supply types and functions that tell the compiler not to re-arrange such instructions, and to insert the appropriate memory barriers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Wait-freedom is the strongest non-blocking guarantee of progress, combining guaranteed system-wide throughput with starvation-freedom.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] An algorithm is wait-free if every operation has a bound on the number of steps the algorithm will take before the operation completes.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] This property is critical for real-time systems and is always nice to have as long as the performance cost is not too high.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] It was shown in the 1980s that all algorithms can be implemented wait-free, and many transformations from serial code, called *universal constructions*, have been demonstrated.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] However, the resulting performance does not in general match even naïve blocking designs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Several papers have since improved the performance of universal constructions, but still, their performance is far below blocking designs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Several papers have investigated the difficulty of creating wait-free algorithms.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] For example, it has been shown that the widely available atomic *conditional* primitives, CAS and LL/SC, cannot provide starvation-free implementations of many common data structures without memory costs growing linearly in the number of threads.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] However, these lower bounds do not present a real barrier in practice, as spending a cache line or exclusive reservation granule (up to 2 KB on ARM) of store per thread in the shared memory is not considered too costly for practical systems.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Typically, the amount of store logically required is a word, but physically CAS operations on the same cache line will collide, and LL/SC operations in the same exclusive reservation granule will collide, so the amount of store physically required is greater.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Wait-free algorithms were rare until 2011, both in research and in practice.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] However, in 2011 Kogan and Petrank presented a wait-free queue building on the CAS primitive, generally available on common hardware.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Their construction expanded the lock-free queue of Michael and Scott, which is an efficient queue often used in practice.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] A follow-up paper by Kogan and Petrank provided a method for making wait-free algorithms fast and used this method to make the wait-free queue practically as fast as its lock-free counterpart.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] A subsequent paper by Timnat and Petrank provided an automatic mechanism for generating wait-free data structures from lock-free ones.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Thus, wait-free implementations are now available for many data-structures.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Under reasonable assumptions, Alistarh, Censor-Hillel, and Shavit showed that lock-free algorithms are practically wait-free.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Thus, in the absence of hard deadlines, wait-free algorithms may not be worth the additional complexity that they introduce.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Lock-freedom allows individual threads to starve but guarantees system-wide throughput.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] An algorithm is lock-free if, when the program threads are run for a sufficiently long time, at least one of the threads makes progress (for some sensible definition of progress).
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In particular, if one thread is suspended, then a lock-free algorithm guarantees that the remaining threads can still make progress.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Hence, if two threads can contend for the same mutex lock or spinlock, then the algorithm is *not* lock-free.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] An algorithm is lock-free if infinitely often operation by some processors will succeed in a finite number of steps.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] For instance, if *N* processors are trying to execute an operation, some of the *N* processes will succeed in finishing the operation in a finite number of steps and others might fail and retry on failure.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] The difference between wait-free and lock-free is that wait-free operation by each process is guaranteed to succeed in a finite number of steps, regardless of the other processors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In general, a lock-free algorithm can run in four phases: completing one's own operation, assisting an obstructing operation, aborting an obstructing operation, and waiting.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Completing one's own operation is complicated by the possibility of concurrent assistance and abortion, but is invariably the fastest path to completion.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] The decision about when to assist, abort or wait when an obstruction is met is the responsibility of a *contention manager*.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] This may be very simple (assist higher priority operations, abort lower priority ones), or may be more optimized to achieve better throughput, or lower the latency of prioritized operations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Correct concurrent assistance is typically the most complex part of a lock-free algorithm, and often very costly to execute: not only does the assisting thread slow down, but thanks to the mechanics of shared memory, the thread being assisted will be slowed, too, if it is still running.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Obstruction-freedom is the weakest natural non-blocking progress guarantee.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] An algorithm is obstruction-free if at any point, a single thread executed in isolation (i.e., with all obstructing threads suspended) for a bounded number of steps will complete its operation.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] All lock-free algorithms are obstruction-free.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Obstruction-freedom demands only that any partially completed operation can be aborted and the changes made rolled back.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Dropping concurrent assistance can often result in much simpler algorithms that are easier to validate.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Preventing the system from continually live-locking is the task of a contention manager.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Some obstruction-free algorithms use a pair of "consistency markers" in the data structure.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Processes reading the data structure first read one consistency marker, then read the relevant data into an internal buffer, then read the other marker, and then compare the markers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] The data is consistent if the two markers are identical.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] Markers may be non-identical when the read is interrupted by another process updating the data structure.
[src:crossbeam-rust/lock-free-and-wait-free-algorithms] In such a case, the process discards the data in the internal buffer and tries again.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In computing, a **memory barrier**, also known as a **membar**, **memory fence** or **fence instruction**, is a type of barrier instruction that causes a central processing unit (CPU) or compiler to enforce an ordering constraint on memory operations issued before and after the barrier instruction.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] This typically means that operations issued prior to the barrier are guaranteed to be performed before operations issued after the barrier.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are necessary because most modern CPUs employ performance optimizations that can result in out-of-order execution.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] This reordering of memory operations (loads and stores) normally goes unnoticed within a single thread of execution, but can cause unpredictable behavior in concurrent programs and device drivers unless carefully controlled.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The exact nature of an ordering constraint is hardware dependent and defined by the architecture's memory ordering model.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Some architectures provide multiple barriers for enforcing different ordering constraints.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Memory barriers are typically used when implementing low-level machine code that operates on memory shared by multiple devices.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Such code includes synchronization primitives and lock-free data structures on multiprocessor systems, and device drivers that communicate with computer hardware.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] When a program runs on a single-CPU machine, the hardware performs the necessary bookkeeping to ensure that the program executes as if all memory operations were performed in the order specified by the programmer (program order), so memory barriers are not necessary.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] However, when the memory is shared with multiple devices, such as other CPUs in a multiprocessor system, or memory-mapped peripherals, out-of-order access may affect program behavior.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] For example, a second CPU may see memory changes made by the first CPU in a sequence that differs from program order.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] A program is run via a process which can be multi-threaded (i.e. a software thread such as pthreads as opposed to a hardware thread).
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Different processes do not share a memory space so this discussion does not apply to two programs, each one running in a different process (hence a different memory space).
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] It applies to two or more (software) threads running in a single process (i.e. a single memory space where multiple software threads share a single memory space).
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Multiple software threads, within a single process, may run concurrently on a multi-core processor.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Initially, memory locations x and f both hold the value 0.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #1 loops while the value of f is zero, then it prints the value of x.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The software thread running on processor #2 stores the value 42 into x and then stores the value 1 into f.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Pseudo-code for the two program fragments is shown below.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The steps of the program correspond to individual processor instructions.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] One might expect the print statement to always print the number "42"; however, if thread #2's store operations are executed out-of-order, it is possible for f to be updated *before* x, and the print statement might therefore print "0".
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Similarly, thread #1's load operations may be executed out-of-order and it is possible for x to be read *before* f is checked, and again the print statement might therefore print an unexpected value.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] For most programs neither of these situations is acceptable.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] A memory barrier must be inserted before thread #2's assignment to f to ensure that the new value of x is visible to other processors at or prior to the change in the value of f.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Another important point is a memory barrier must also be inserted before thread #1's access to x to ensure the value of x is not read prior to seeing the change in the value of f.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] If the processor's store operations are executed out-of-order, the hardware module may be triggered before data is ready in memory.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] For another illustrative example (a non-trivial one that arises in actual practice), see double-checked locking.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In the case of the ARM architecture family, the DMB, DSB and ISB instructions are used.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In the case of the RISC-V architecture, the FENCE instruction is used.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In the case of the x86 architecture, the MFENCE, LFENCE, and SFENCE instructions are used.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Multithreaded programs usually use synchronization primitives provided by a high-level programming environment—such as Java or .NET—or an application programming interface (API) such as POSIX Threads or Windows API.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Synchronization primitives such as mutexes and semaphores are provided to synchronize access to resources from parallel threads of execution.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] These primitives are usually implemented with the memory barriers required to provide the expected memory visibility semantics.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In such environments explicit use of memory barriers is not generally necessary.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Memory barrier instructions address reordering effects only at the hardware level.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Compilers may also reorder instructions as part of the program optimization process.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Although the effects on parallel program behavior can be similar in both cases, in general, it is necessary to take separate measures to inhibit compiler reordering optimizations for data that may be shared by multiple threads of execution.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] In C and C++, the volatile keyword was intended to allow C and C++ programs to directly access memory-mapped I/O.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Memory-mapped I/O generally requires that the reads and writes specified in source code happen in the exact order specified with no omissions.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Omissions or reorderings of reads and writes by the compiler would break the communication between the program and the device accessed by memory-mapped I/O.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] A C or C++ compiler may not omit reads from and writes to volatile memory locations, nor may it reorder read/writes relative to other such actions for the same volatile location (variable).
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The keyword volatile *does not guarantee a memory barrier* to enforce cache-consistency.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] Therefore, the use of volatile alone is not sufficient to use a variable for inter-thread communication on all systems and processors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/memory-barrier] The C and C++ standards prior to C11 and C++11 do not address multiple threads (or multiple processors), and as such, the usefulness of volatile depends on the compiler and hardware.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:crossbeam-rust/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:crossbeam-rust/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
